Rating: 4
This can be adapted to give 2 different kinds of tortilla soup: Soup #1 is basically a clear thin broth heavily lime flavored. The changes to the recipe can be altered with omitting the water (or not) and adding the equivalent amount of additional chicken broth. I choose to also increase the cumin to 1/2 teaspoon and omitting the crushed red pepper and adding 1/8-1/4 tsp of cayenne instead. Left over shredded baked chicken works great in this. My family is not particularly fond of the cilantro spice so this is omitted. I also use the juice of an entire lime (or approximately 4 Tablespoons). The bay leaf can be omitted as well without much of a deficit. Soup #2: For a heartier soup, I include all the same changes as listed above, but I saute' a large onion with my garlic 1-2 cloves first and then add to the ingredients and bring to a boil. I add a 14 1/2 oz can of black beans (drained and rinsed) and an 8.5-11 oz can of corn or corn with chilis. This definitely makes the soup more filling. Both can be served with a platter of topping choices that your guests/family can put on top: avacado (diced), Oaxaca or Queso Fresco cheese (or just 4-5 Cheese Mexican shredded), sour cream, grilled/crispy onions, and jalapeno pepppers. The tortilla strips can be a good quality bagged chip from the store if you don't have the time to make your own fresh strips from tortillas. This is fast and quite good when you feel like soup but don't have a lot of time to get it on the table (The story of my life).

